Title: The John Wayne Ultimate Film Collection

reviewText: In the early 1930's, before securing fame as Hollywood's foremost action hero, John Wayne cut his teeth in the business by playing romantic second leads opposite some of the era's most popular actresses, as well as starring in a long string of quickie westerns. Also during this time, Wayne made three 12 chapter serials for Mascot Pictures, a low budget studio founded by producer Nat Levine. None were westerns, but they did showcase Wayne's trademark easy going style and his knack at handling action oriented material even at this early stage in his career.In SHADOW OF THE EAGLE (1932), the Duke is a stunt flier at a carnival determined to reveal the identity of "The Eagle", a mysterious villain who is blackmailing the directors of an airplane factory over a stolen invention.THE HURRICANE EXPRESS (1932) concerns a saboteur who calls himself "The Wrecker" and his schemes to put the L & R Railroad out of business. Airline pilot Wayne, whose engineer father was killed in an accident caused by "The Wrecker", swears to bring the criminal to justice.THE THREE MUSKETEERS (1933) features Wayne as one of a trio of Foreign Legion pilots who must quell an Arab uprising led by the evil "El Shaitan".The fact that Mascot was a Poverty Row outfit whose production budgets were restricted meant that they didn't employ expensive special effects or process photography. An exception is SHADOW OF THE EAGLE, which includes some animated footage of sky writing courtesy of the Disney studios. Mostly though, the action sequences involved real situations shot on location, many of which required the young, athletic Wayne to perform his own stunts. To further cut costs, retakes were kept at a bare minimum which meant the first take often got printed. This economical approach adds a spontaneity and a gritty authenticity which greatly enhances the entertainment value of these serials. The extensive location photography shows us how much of the Hollywood area was still rural in the early '30's. Contrary to the widely held opinion that Wayne's acting left much to be desired during his novice years, the actor already reveals an engagingly sincere and unaffected style in these cliffhangers that would endear him to moviegoers for decades to come.All three complete serials are available from Passport Video, which offers the best quality on these public domain titles that I've ever come across. For extras, we get the original trailers and a 25 minute retrospective of the Duke's career.This DVD collection is an absolute must have for John Wayne and serial fans alike, and gives us a good look at a still relatively underrated actor during his "bread and butter" days.Highly recommended.
summary: A YOUNG DUKE AS SERIAL HERO

reviewText: Passport Video and Koch Entertainment Distribution present "The John Wayne Cliffhanger Collection" (1932/33)(Dolby digitally remastered)...relive those thrilling days from the early '30s and '40swhen John Wayne took us up into the skies to excitingadventures....some of the best cliffhangers ever to grace the Saturday MatineeScreen...just remember double thrills, chills, mystery and suspense...hitting the bull's eyewith excitement...don't miss any of the John Wayne features loaded with action that will leaveyou wanting more of his high adventuresFirst up is "SHADOW OF THE EAGLE" (1932 - B&W;) (12 Chapters), under director Ford Beebe, produced by Nat Levine, original screenplay & story by Colbert Clark, Wyndham Gittens and Forbe Beebe....the cast include John Wayne (Craig McCoy), Dorothy Gulliver( Jean Gregory), Edward Hearn (Col. Nathan B. Gregory), Richard Tucker (Maj. Evans, company owner), Lloyd Whitlock (Green, a director),  Walter Miller (Danby, a director ), Edmund Burns (Clark, a director), Pat O'Malley (Ames, a director), Kenneth Harlan (Ward, a director),  Little Billy' Rhodes (Billy Little, the midget), Ivan Linow (Heinie, the strongman), James Bradbury Jr. (Henry, the ventriloquist), Ernie Adams (Frederick 'Pat' Kelly, the barker), Roy D'Arcy (Henchman Gardner), Bud Osborne (Henchman Tim Moore), YakimaCanutt (Henchman Boyle), Billy West (Bob, the clown ), Monte Montague (Callahan, Policeman at circus).......our story has seversal questions will The Eagle use sky writing to make threats against a corporation...can Edward Hearn who owns a travelling fairground and is thought to be the Eagle succeed in his evil plot against all that is good...will John Wayne who is a pilot go searching for the Eagle when Hearn's turns up missing....all of this and more await your viewing pleasure in a 12 Chapter Mascot Pictures thrilling serial adventure that is action packed. . . . . . . Special footnote, actor John Wayne once said, "Every country in the world loved the folklore of the West - the music, the dress, the excitement, everything that was associated with the opening of a new territory. It took everybody out of their own little world - The cowboy lasted a hundred years, created more songs and prose and poetry than any other folk figure - The closest thing was the Japanese samurai. Now, I wonder who'll continue it...His performance as Ethan Edwards in "The Searchers" (1956) is ranked #23 on Premiere Magazine's 100 Greatest Movie Characters of All Time...Of his many film roles, his personal favorite was that of Ethan Edwards from The Searchers (1956). Wayne even went so far as to name his son Ethan after that character...The inscription on the Congressional Gold Medal awarded to him in 1979 reads, simply, "John Wayne, American."...After meeting the late Superman star Christopher Reeve at the 1979 Academy Awards, Wayne turned to Cary Grant and said "This is our new man. He's taking over."...Turned down the role of Marshal Dillon on "Gunsmoke" (1955) because he did not want to commit to a weekly TV series. He recommended his friend James Arness for the role, and gave the on camera introduction in the pilot episode...I would like to be remembered, well...the Mexicans have a phrase, 'Feo fuerte y formal'. Which means; he was ugly, strong and had dignity."Chapter Titles:1. The Carnival Mystery2. Pinholes3. The Eagle Strikes4. The Man of a Million Voices5. The Telephone Cipher6. Code of the Carnival7.
